RDF Proxy
=========

Simple proxy application to serve collections of RDF resources from a SPARQL
endpoint as Web documents via HTTP content neogotiation.

Resource mapping approach
-------------------------

The application maps resources URIs to documents followind the usual convention,
where a fragment identifier is assumed to be part of the document URI to which
the fragment is appended. For every resources identified as part of the
requested document, the application collects the Concise BoundedDescription,
and returns a serialisation containing all of these descriptions.

The description only includes blank nodes within one hop of the document URI,
to keep the complexity of the resulting query manageable.

Proxy server support
--------------------

The following HTTP proxy headers will be taken into consideration when
identifying actual resource URIs:

* X-Forwarded-Host: Substituted for the host value when provided
* X-Forwarded-Proto: Substituted for the protocol value when provided

Dependencies
------------

* Python: https://www.python.org/
* RDFLib: https://github.com/RDFLib/rdflib
* Flask: https://github.com/pallets/flask

Development setup
-----------------

This repository supports Visual Studio Code Dev Containers, which is the
recommended way to open the repository and do development work. This helps
ensure the required dependencies and extensions are all present,
and may help isolate PyPi-sourced packages to avoid potential problems.

There exists also a Podman Compose file under example/, to allow running both
Apache Jena Fuseki as a SPARQL endpoint, and the application code itself.

Configuration options
---------------------

The following environment variables are used to configure the data source,
and are passed on to RDFLib's SPARQLStore:

* SPARQL_ENDPOINT: The endpoint URI, passed to RDFLib
* SPARQL_USERNAME: The username to use (optional)
* SPARQL_PASSWORD: The password to use (optional)

The following options exist for configuring the application itself:

* TEMPLATE_PATH: The path to HTML templates, defaults to /usr/share/rdfgpp

Additionally, the Flask application configuration is loaded from the default
prefixed environment variables.

Template mapping and context
----------------------------

The template is selected based on the types of the document URI.
For example, if the document URI is declared as having rdf:type of
schema:BlogPosting, then BlogPosting.html is selected as the template.

Errors are also converted into triples, using the schema.org vocabulary.
Errors have the type schema:Error, and thus use the Error.html template.

The following variables are made available to the templates:

* graph: The output as RDFLib Graph, with identifier set to document URI
* timestamp: The current timestamp in UTC as datetime.datetime
* type: The type string used to select the template

